The problem isn't complexity, a story can remain engaging even if it has a lot of moving parts, look at stuff like the Sopranos. The thing about complexity is that it can be turnoff to most readers if those moving parts aren't given the right amount of focus, or if they aren't communicated to the reader effectively.
I completely disagree with your take on mystery being a bad genre for this thread especially for stories with less emphasis on romance. Mysteries are all about gathering and vetting information to come to an accurate solution to a problem, usually a conclusion on how a crime was comitted and who committed it. Good /hmofa/ mysteries can design crimes or inciting incidents around the unique traits of certain species, or use the differences in sensory perception or culture between humans and anthros to provide investigators with different sets of clues.
I've worked with Happy before. He's aware that his stories contain a lot of detail, and that they can be difficult to follow because of how he chooses to spotlight that detail. He believes that altering his style will deviate the story too much from his original vision. He and I hold different philosophies, but I can respect his resolve to maintain his artistic integrity over pandering.
